  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over time:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, US)\n- First international efforts to address financial crimes\n- Limited regulatory frameworks\n\n2. 1980s-1990s Developments\n- FATF established in 1989\n- Increasing international cooperation\n- More comprehensive reporting requirements\n- Enhanced customer identification protocols\n\n3. Post-9/11 Legislation\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Expanded anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- Stricter requirements for financial institutions\n- Enhanced terrorism financing prevention\n\n4. Global Regulatory Trends\n- Enhanced due diligence requirements\n- Risk-based approaches to monitoring\n- Increased transparency in financial transactions\n- Cross-border information sharing\n\n5. Recent Technological Adaptations\n- Cryptocurrency regulations\n- Digital transaction monitoring\n- Advanced data analytics\n- Machine learning for suspicious activity detection\n\n6. Current Focus Areas\n- Beneficial ownership transparency\n- Comprehensive risk assessment\n- Cybercrime prevention\n- International collaboration\n- Sanctions enforcement\n\nThe legislation has progressively become more sophisticated, comprehensive, and technologically integrated to address evolving financial crime methods.",
